===Etymology===
From Old English [[broþor|brōðor]], from Germanic *''brōþēr'', from Indo-European *''bʰrāter-''.  Cognates include (''from Germanic'') Dutch [[broeder]], German [[Bruder]], Swedish [[broder]]; (''from Indo-European'') Latin [[frater]], Russian [[брат]] (brat), Greek [[φράτηρ]] (frater), Latvian [[brãlis]], Welsh [[brawd]].

